# Asynchronous Programming Best Practices

## When to Use Async
- I/O-bound operations (network requests, file operations, database queries)
- Operations that can benefit from concurrent execution
- Long-running tasks that shouldn't block the main thread
- Real-time applications (WebSockets, streaming)

## Async Patterns
- Use async/await for cleaner asynchronous code
- Return promises/futures consistently
- Avoid mixing sync and async code carelessly
- Use appropriate concurrency primitives (semaphores, locks, queues)
- Implement proper error handling with try/catch or .catch()

## Error Handling
- Always handle promise rejections
- Use try/catch blocks with async/await
- Implement timeout mechanisms for long operations
- Log errors with context for debugging
- Provide meaningful error messages

## Performance Considerations
- Don't await unnecessarily - use Promise.all/asyncio.gather for parallel ops
- Limit concurrent operations to avoid overwhelming resources
- Use connection/thread pools appropriately
- Implement backpressure for streams
- Monitor async task queues and prevent buildup

## Testing
- Use mocking for async dependencies
- Test both success and error cases
- Use testing frameworks with async support
- Test timeout scenarios
- Verify proper cleanup of async resources

## Common Pitfalls
- Forgetting to await async calls
- Creating race conditions with shared state
- Not handling errors properly (unhandled rejections)
- Blocking the event loop with CPU-intensive work
- Memory leaks from unclosed connections or hanging promises
